<h2 CLASS="SECTION">
<a NAME="INST_SOURCES_SWORD_MODULES"></a> Installation of modules</h2>
SWORD currently supports 3 types of modules: Bibles, dictionaries and commentaries.
In order for sword and bibletime to be useful these modules must be installed.
<p>Sword modules can be installed manually (the manual method is descbed
in the bibletime handbook) or with
<a href="inst_sources.html#INST_SOURCES_SWORD_INSTALLMGR">installmgr</a>.
Installmgr is provided as part of the sword package. The directions here
will install the sword modules to the same location with either the manual
method or the installmgr. However if you wish to customize the location
of your sword module directory, you must use the manual method.
<div CLASS="SECTION">
<h3 CLASS="SECTION">
<a NAME="INST_SOURCES_SWORD_INSTALLMGR"></a> Sword installmgr</h3>
To compile installmgr first sword must have been compiled.

<p>Find the file <tt>libsword.so</tt>, sword probably installed it to
<tt>/usr/local/sword/lib</tt>
unless you customized the installation.
<p>In order that installmgr (and also bibletime) can find this shared library
open a text editor and add <tt>/usr/local/sword/lib</tt> to the end of
<tt>/etc/ld.so.conf</tt>.
<p>Now you are ready to compile installmgr.
<p>CD to your sword source and open the directory
<tt>.../sword/apps/X11/InstallMgr</tt>.
Now in a shell do:
<br>&nbsp;
<table BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" BGCOLOR="#E0E0E0" >
<tr>
<td>
<pre CLASS="SCREEN">&nbsp;ldconfig
&nbsp;./configure
&nbsp;make
&nbsp;su
&nbsp;make install</pre>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>Now in a shell as su you can run installmgr by typing
<tt>/usr/local/bin/installmgr</tt>.
<p>If this was successful, there are two options for loading text modules
into sword.
<ul
>Options>Manage remote sources. -- This option is used to get modules from the sword CD.
<p>Options>Local Path -- If you have unzipped sources point this to your
local module repository. All of the available modules will be displayed,
and are available for installation.</ul>

<div
CLASS="SECTION"
>
<h4 CLASS="SECTION">
<a NAME="INST_SOURCES_SWORD_INSTMGR_REP"></a> Setting up your repository</h4>
Download modules from <a href="http://www.crosswire.org" TARGET="_top">Crosswire
Bible Society</a> use the zipped up modules (modulename.zip), not the windows
executable compressed files (modulename.exe).
<p>Create a directory for your module repository, <tt>$HOME/sword_modules</tt>
for example.
<p>Open a program that can uncompress zip files. Such as gnozup or archiver.
Command line tools can also be used, to find which ones are installed on
your system do a <b>man -k zip</b>
<p>Use your unzipping program to extract the module files into <tt>$HOME/sword_modules</tt>.
All of the files will be placed into the correct subdirectories. If you
wish to add modules later remember to unzip to <tt>$HOME/sword_modules</tt>.</div>

<div
CLASS="SECTION"
>
<h4 CLASS="SECTION">
<a NAME="INST_SOURCES_SWORD_INSTMGR_CFG"></a> Setting up the sword configuration
file.</h4>
Instructions for the sword configuration file can be found in the section
"The
SWORD configuration file" in the section of the bibletime handbook covering the manual installation
of the sword modules.</div>

<div
CLASS="SECTION"
>
<h4 CLASS="SECTION">
<a NAME="INST_SOURCES_SWORD_INSTMGR_LOAD"></a> Using installmanager to
load sword modules.</h4>
You must start installmgr as root for it to be able to load modules. Start
it with these commands:
<br>&nbsp;
<table BORDER=0 WIDTH="100%" BGCOLOR="#E0E0E0" >
<tr>
<td>
<pre CLASS="SCREEN">&nbsp;[me@localhost user]$ su
&nbsp;Password:
&nbsp;[root@localhost user]# /usr/local/bin/installmgr</pre>
</td>
</tr>
</table>

<p>You will now see the installmgr window. You will need to use <span
CLASS="GUIMENU"
>options>local
path</span
> to point to your local module repository.
<p>Now the available modules will be shown on the left pane and the installed
modules on the right. All you need to do is select modules in the left
pane and click install to make them available to sword and bibletime.
<br>&nbsp;
<br>&nbsp;</div>
</div>

